A potential benefit of the group as program of rules idea is that it may be possible to back up to some point in a running program. This assumes that a matched rule tracks its location in the input stream, so to back up, revert to that point, and run the rule again. Not so useful unless you have the ability to step thru rules (ideally ignoring rules you have no interest in, maybe by using a stop in rule list??).
    Maybe cannot do this in a compiled program, but should be able to do it in an interpreter. OTOH the stop in rule list would work even with a compiled program, tho you would not have the flexibility that an interpreter would provide. The problem comes when the problem happens deep in an input stream. ITC need to be able to recognize the point at which rule monitoring should start and trigger it. Can do this as a directive added to the rule. A crappy way to implement the stop in rule list would be using directives added to the rules to be stopped (check status of trigger, stop if triggered - have to use debugger stops)
    BTW should add atStart and atEnd as alternatives to before in directives (would avoid some of the hunt for code matching)

