    This would be a new feature (useful in a registry test), that defines a token and then enables testing against the current token rather than against the raw input stream. Not sure how to implement it. Ideally, the token could be defined by any potentially really complex rule set that results in a group w/string text to be tested against.
    Current issue is how to associate a token as input to a rule?
        I am thinking to define a token by specifying @ that sets atTarget. Next I need a way to let the parser know to test against the token rather than against the input stream. If an attribute is a target, make it the current token. If there is a current token, test against it.
        When to turn off token. I am thinking after the first test that uses it. If the test is a rule, the input stream gets diverted to the text of the token, and after the rule test, the token gets forgotten and the input stream reverts.

            Will need an input stream stack, so every time a token is encountered, the current stream is pushed onto the stack and the token becomes the input stream. When done w/token, the stream stacked is popped. Might work. Needs testing.
